reak: after-white-space;" class=3D"">Hello All,<div class=3D"">I=E2=80=99ve=
 followed this thread pretty closely as a trans game studies scholar, and w=
hat I=E2=80=99ve read here isn=E2=80=99t really reassuring. Given how LGBTQ=
 folks often face harassment even in supposedly safe and accepting places, =
reassurances that it will *probably* be fine, and the government will *prob=
ably* look the other way for foreigners presenting on queer experiences and=
 studies, and queer participants will be *relatively* safe ring pretty holl=
ow. I was particularly alarmed when I read that LGB is probably fine, but t=
he Ts might have to worry. I don=E2=80=99t doubt that that is likely an acc=
urate reflection of the situation given how trans, genderqueer, and nonbina=
ry folks are most frequently targeted for harassment, assault, and legislat=
ion. However a situation where only some members of the LGBTQ community are=
 welcome or safe isn=E2=80=99t inclusive or helpful.</div><div class=3D""><=
br class=3D""></div><div class=3D"">The teleconferencing option, while bett=
er than nothing, feels like a bandage on the larger issue=E2=80=94presentin=
g from a distance often involves just giving the presentation and being inv=
olved with one panel and then leaving, which means missing out on a lot of =
the discussion and networking that makes conferencing valuable in the first=
 place. It might be the best option available for providing safe presentati=
on options to queer and particularly trans game studies scholars if the con=
ference is to continue in St. Petersburg, but it=E2=80=99s not an ideal or =
particularly inclusive solution. I don=E2=80=99t have an easy answer to thi=
s because there isn=E2=80=99t one, but it seems to me that the conference h=
as to decide between safety and support for LGBTQ game scholars and the imp=
ortance of holding the conference in different locations that allow more pe=
ople to participate. Whatever is decided here and moving forward, I think i=
t=E2=80=99s important that the safety of queer folks not be sacrificed in t=
he name of holding a conference in more locations, and ideally finding conf=
erence locations that accomplish both. I do hope that the St. Petersburg co=
nference will provide opportunities to present for folks who aren=E2=80=99t=
 able to make other international conferences and particularly local LGBTQ =
folks, though it seems that they too might have to be careful about what th=
ey present at the conference.</div><div class=3D""><br class=3D""></div><di=
v class=3D"">I would also humbly submit that if you=E2=80=99re working on a=
 trans or queer game as a cisgendered and/or straight scholar and think tha=
t the queerness of that game is coincidental or not the main point, that yo=
u may need to think carefully about your positionality in relationship to t=
hat game, how you are using it, and to what ends. The minimization of queer=
ness in games is a longstanding heteronormative project, and it would be di=
sappointing to see game studies scholarship continue to contribute to it.<b=
